are expected to have no emotional connection to the subjects they study. Yet is this possible? Following feminist traditions, Vulnerable Witness centers the researcher and challenges readers to reflect on how grieving is part of the research process and, by extension, is a political act. Through thirteen reflective essays the book theorizes the role of grief in the doing of research—from methodological choices, fieldwork and analysis, engagement with individuals, and places of study to the manner in which scholars write and talk about their subjects. Combining personal stories from early career scholars, advocates, and senior faculty, the book shares a breadth of emotional engagement at various career stages and explores the transformative possibilities that emerge from being enmeshed with one's own research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGriefxPolitical aspects. 0aResearchxPolitical aspects. 0aResearchxPsychological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh1 aAbrell, Elan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoarder Giles, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Jessie Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuomo, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoubleday, Kalli F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElena García, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillespie, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillespie, Kathryn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIsaacs, Jenny R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopez, Patricia J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct